"{\"uid\": \"lifeandstylemag.com-posts-is-u-s-olympic-swimmer-katie-ledecky-married-dating-history\", \"text\": \"Michael Reaves/Getty Images  Fans of U.S. swimmerKatie Ledeckyare cheering her on in her fourthOlympicappearance. Many are wondering if she's married or has a significant other who is supporting her as she competes in the July 2024 Paris Games.  Katie is notmarriedand there is no indication she has ever tied the knot with anyone.  The Olympian keeps her social media pages mainly about her professional accomplishments, training and sponsorship deals. Katie reps Core Power protein shakes, LaCroix sparkling water, Athleta workout wear and the electronics brand Panasonic.  While the most decorated female swimmer in history does not reveal anything about her romantic life on social media, Katie has shared how much her family members mean to her.  In a June 3, 2024,Instagram post, the Washington. D.C. native showed her maternal grandmother holding a copy of Katie's memoir,Just Add Water.  \\\"My Grandma Hagan\\u2026she's lived in 11 different decades. Find out what she has meant to me in JustAdd Water, my book out on June 11th,\\\" she wrote in the caption along with additional photos with of her grandmother over the years. One snapshot showed the pair holding Katie's medal haul from the 2016 Rio de Janeiro Olympics, where she took home four gold and one silver medal  Katie has also shared numerous photos alongside her older brother,Michael Ledecky, over the years on her Instagram page, as the siblings are incredibly close.  Katie made her Olympic debut at the 2012 London games when she was 15 years old. In the years since, fans have watched her grow from a talented teen into the most powerful and accomplished female swimmer of all time.  She went on to compete in the 2016 Rio games, followed by the 2020 Tokyo Olympics, where she took home two gold medals. Paris 2024 marks Katie's fourth Olympic games.  \\\"The (2028) Olympics being in L.A. is very appealing. Not very many athletes get an opportunity to compete in a home Games,\\\" she told NBC in May 2024. \\\"I definitely at this point am planning on going through 2028 \\u2026 whether I compete in one event, multiple events, a relay, whatever.\\\"  \\\"I have been [at The University of] Florida for about two and a half years now. I have really enjoyed it. I have been able to train with some of the top male distance swimmers in the country and in the world, so that's been beneficial for my training and I try to keep them on their toes as well. And it's just a really fun environment,\\\" the Stanford University graduate toldPeoplein June 2024.  \\\"I want to make sure that I am being a leader for our team, both in and out of the pool and making sure that the younger swimmers feel like they belong on that team and belong at the Olympic level, Katie continued, adding that she wanted to make \\\"sure that they feel comfortable and confident going out there and competing with the best in the world.\\\"  \\\"It's a little surreal. I mean, I do not think I would have expected to necessarily still be at this level this many years later,\\\" Katie toldPeopleahead of the Olympic trials in Indianapolis, Indiana, in June 2024. \\\"I would not have been able to see into the future that I would be competing in 2024. So yeah, I do not take it for granted. I do not take these opportunities for granted, and I just try to enjoy each day of the training and the process.\\\"  Conversation  All comments are subject to ourCommunity Guidelines. Life & Style does not endorse \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\tthe opinions and views shared by our readers in our comment sections. Our comments section is a place \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\twhere readers can engage in healthy, productive, lively, and respectful discussions. Offensive language, \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\thate speech, personal attacks, and/or defamatory statements are not permitted. Advertising or spam is \\t\\t\\t\\t\\t\\talso prohibited.  Life & Style has affiliate 